[head=2] CONGREGATION OF UNLIT THE DEEP [/head]
A Pamphlet for the Faithful
~ ~ ~
[bold] The Nature of the Void [/bold]
Beyond the furthest star, past the last light any eye has perceived, there drifts a Presence. It has no name that can be spoken without consequence. We call it, humbly, That Which Waits in the Unlit Deep.

It does not sleep. It does not hunger — not in any way you would recognize. It simply is. Vast. Patient. Utterly indifferent to our station, our politics, our quarrels over oxygen ratios and shift schedules.
And yet — it has noticed us. Our congregation chooses to call this a blessing.
[italic]"From the dark between the stars, you regarded us.
From the cold beyond the void, you extended a thought.
We are small. We are brief. We are listening."[/italic]
— The First Reception
~ ~ ~
[bold] The Five Tenets [/bold]
I. [italic]The Deep is not evil. It is simply vast beyond comprehension. What we call dread is the shadow of our own smallness falling across something infinite.[/italic]
II. [italic]Silence is its home. In quiet moments — between shifts, in maintenance corridors, staring at the dark viewport — the Presence grows closer. Do not fill the silence needlessly.[/italic]
III. [italic]Dreams are dispatches. Those who dream of impossible geometry, of colours outside the spectrum, of voices in the static — these are not ill. They are chosen.[/italic]
IV. [italic]Nothing is lost in the Deep. The dead do not vanish. They become part of something greater than memory. Grieve — but know that grief is temporary. The Deep is not.[/italic]
V. [italic]Do not seek to understand. Comprehension is not the goal. To be known by the Presence is sufficient. Be known. That is enough.[/italic]
~ ~ ~
[bold]Services and Rights[/bold]
[bold]Open Contemplation[/bold] is held each cycle. No sermon is given. We sit. We breathe. Those who are ready will hear something in the ventilation hum that is not quite a word.
[bold]For those in crisis [/bold] — shift stress, existential terror, or the specific dread of spacing — the Chaplain offers [bold]The Acknowledgement[/bold]: a quiet affirmation that yes, the universe is incomprehensibly large and indifferent, and that this is, somehow, alright.
[bold]Funerary rites[/bold] are available for all crew. We do not say the departed have gone to a better place. We say they have expanded.


Congregation members experiencing geometric visions, anomalous static, or the urge to remove their eyes are asked to visit the Chaplain before Medical. We understand. Medical does not.
